Chronic conditions like diabetes, hypertension, pulmonary diseases, and others are able to be identified at earlier stages. Early identification means early intervention which can save lives and improve quality of life. Our goal is to help patients and care providers with tools to manage home-based care. Allowing care providers to monitor, intervene, and assist with faster diagnosis and recovery from many diseases. Syncline Health is dedicated to creating a health care system where preventable diseases are prevented and diagnosed early. ​

Headquarters Regions: Greater New York Area, East Coast, Northeastern US
Full Description: Sooloos is a pathfinder and pioneer in the world of media-server products. Sooloos, formed in 2004, produced a groundbreaking suite of products in the early days of the digital media revolution. Based on early work by Danny Dulai and Enno Vandermeer, this small team brought a distributed multi-zone digital music system to market in 2005. Unlike the competing media server products of the 2000s, Sooloos didn't just solve the infrastructure problems of content import, storage, and streaming. Its product offering was uniquely focused on the user experience of browsing and listening to music, with an emphasis on graphically rich and tactile user interface available on a dedicated 17" touch panel device. Sooloos developed elegant solutions to a variety of product and technical problems including media backup, remote system health monitoring, audio analysis for crossfade and volume leveling, music recognition and metadata retrieval, high-performance GUI rendering, and low-latency audio streaming. Sooloos was acquired by Meridian Audio in December 2008.

Full Description: San Francisco, CA - Online boutique Adela Mei brings petite shoppers a unique shopping destination and easier shopping experience, with a tightly edited selection of modern, contemporary clothing for women who stand “tall” at 5’4” and under. With a focus on silhouette and proportion, the online boutique is curated to ensure a great fit for petites. The boutique’s co-owners, Sasha Moyer and Stacy Leung were inspired to open their unique concept when they found themselves constantly having to alter or return items bought online because it was hard to judge the fit shown on the 5’10” models on traditional retailer websites. Both petite women themselves, they named Adela Mei after their grandmothers, who were petite fashion-forward women as well. The dynamic duo approaches the selection at Adela Mei with a razor focus, measuring and testing every piece. The site provides detailed measurements and fit suggestions for every size offered, ensuring that shoppers know exactly what they’re getting before they click “buy.” The clothing is presented on models with petite frames, so customers can see exactly how the items fit on someone with a similar height.
